{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_emmental_ver01/data/sn83045293/00517012452/1920102601/0069.xml":{"full_text":"If an idea is true, you can\u2019t suppress it,\nand if it is false it does not need to be sup\npressed\u2014it will suppress itself.\u2014Horace\nTraubel.\nVol. 9\u2014No. 274.\nFINDINGS\nBY\nVICTOR L. BERGER\nLa Follette\u2019s Mouthpiece\u2014\nThe Capital Tinies\u2014\nSpeaks,\nIn Unmistakable Terms\nAbout Kleczka and Staf\nford.\nCalls Kleczka a Renegade\nand Stafford an Old-Time\nTool of the \u201cInterests.\u201d\nSays That Neither Is En\ntitled to Progressive\nVotes.\nWe agree.\nUnder the caption\u2014\u201c Progre\nssives for Election Only\u201d\u2014I find\nin The Capital Times (Madison),\nSenator R. M. La Follette\u2019s ac\nknowledged mouthpiece, ths fol\nlowing:\n\n\u201cThe aid of progressives is be\ning sought in Milwaukee for the\nelection of John C. Kleczka and\nWilliam H. Stafford to congress*\n\u201cWe are unable to\u2019 see how\nthese gentlemen can make any\nvalid claim to the support of\nprogressives on their records of\nthe past few years.\n\u201cKleczka 1 is one of the long list\nof renegade progressives who\nslipped when the real test came,\n\u201cIn the days when everybody\nwas progressive, Kleczka was\nknown as aLa Follette man. He\nattained to considerable political\nprominence in his own locality\nthrough his identification with\nthe progressive movement.\n\u201cDuring the war no one was\nmore bitter toward the senator\nthan was Kleczka. He traveled\nwith that group that took their\ncue from the British serving\nMilwaukee Journal and Kleczka\nparroted the denunciations of the\nsenator with the rest of the fake\nloud mouthed \u2018patriots\u2019 of Mil\nwaukee. Since he has been in,\nCongress his record has been sat\nisfactory to the crowd that has\nbeen trading on patriotism.\n\n\u201cStafford, unlike Kleczka, has\nalways been reactionary.\n\u201cThe \u2018Loyalist crowd\u2019 in Mil\nwaukee has finally trotted Staf\nford out tp beat Berger because\nStafford (Voted against war.\nThink of it, \u2014this group in Mil\nwaukee comprising the Associa\ntion of Commerce, the bankers,\nThe Milwaukee Journal and all\nof the rest of that crew which\ntried to kill public men on their\nstand on the war, forced to trot\nout a candidate who voted\nagainst war th a desperate at\ntempt to beat Berger.\n(Incidentally: It is only fair to\nMr. Stafford to admit that he\nvoted for all the war measures\nsuch as the Espionage act, the\nConscription law and all the rest.\nEditor Leader.)\n\u201cBut then, the war is over and\nthese interests know Stafford.\n\u201cThey know that when the\nballots are taken in Congress that\nStafford will always line up in\nbehalf of privilege and wealth.\nStafford\u2019s record in the past is an\neloquent testimonial to that fact.\n\u201cThe Capital Times believes\nthat men who have met the test\nshould be chosen to represent the\npeople and not the fair weather\nkind who are progressive when\nthe track is clear and the going\nis good.\u2019\u2019\nThus speaks The Capital\nTimes.\n\nAnd coming to think it over:\nThis is rather a bitter-sweet\nand left-handed endorsement of\nthe two Socialists running in the\n4th and in the sth Congressional\ndistrict.\nThat the Socialists can be de\npended upon to vote for truly\nprogressive measures \u2014in all\nkinds of weather \u2014needs no fur\nther proof, of course.\nIn sact \u2014about 14 or 15 years\nago, Mr. La Follette, then gov\nernor of the state, told me more\nthan once that he could more\nconfidently rely upon the vote of\nthe Socialists in the legislature\nfor certain bills, than upon his\nown men. To which statement I\ncheerfully agreed.\n\nThe Capital Times, therefore,\ncould have made the statement\nvery much stronger without of\nfending our friend Bob.\nThe Times, for instance, could\nhave said\u2014that Kleczka is no\nTurn to Page Pour, Column One,\nBanks See Business Failures Here\nBODY OF M\u2019SWINEY\nWILL LIE IN STATE\nImpressive Funeral Honors\nWill Be Accorded Martyred\nLord Mayor of Cork.\nBODYGUARD OF FIFTY\nSINN FEINERS ARRIVE\nUnnatural Calm Pervades Ire\nland \u2014Another Irish Hunger\nStriker Dies.\nBULLETIN.\nBy The United Prese.\nNEW YORK Sinn Fein\nsympathizers throughout the\nUnited States today were or\nganizing mass meetings to be\nheld Sunday in mourning for\nthe death of Lord Mayor Mac-\nSwiney. The call for these\nmeetings, sent to 1,300 branches\nof the American commission on\nIrish independence by Frank P.\nWalsh, chairman, suggested\nthat speakers urge the Ameri\ncan state department to recog\nnize an Irish republic. It also\nwas suggested that bells be\ntolled Sunday noon and serv\nices for MacSwiney said in all\nchurches.\nBY LLOYD ALLEN.\nStaff Correspondent\nThe United Press\nLONDON \u2014Impressive funeral\nhonors will be accorded Terence\nMacSwiney, who began life as a\nclerk and died in a spectacular\nmanner for Ireland.\nThe home office promised to\nday there will be no interference\nwith plans of Irish leaders who\nannodneed MacSwiney\u2019s body will\nlie in state in St. George\u2019s cathe\ndral, to be carried later in solemn\nprocession to entrain for the\njourney ta'W4iMr grave.\nOfficials asid the only restriction\non the fuheral services will be that\nno Sinn Fein firing squad will be\npermitted to officiate at the grave.\nOne of MacSwiney\u2019s last requests\nwas that the funeral orations be\npronounced in Gaelic. There was\nno official opposition to that.\nBodyguard of 50.\nThe deputy lord mayor of Cork\narlved here today with a bodyguard\nof 50 Sinn Felners and representa\ntives of many Irish societies. It was\nreported the dail eireann, the Irish\nparliament, may attend the funeral\nin a body.\nAfter the inquest, expected to be\nconcluded Wednesday morning,\nMacSwiney\u2019s body wH be taken to\nSt.| George\u2019s cathedral. It will lie\nin state, under guard of his follow\ners, until 11 a. m. Thursday. At\nthat hour solemn high mass will be\ncelebrated by Bishop Mannix and\nBiship Cotter, of Portsmouth.\nDate in the afternoon a funeral\nprocession will be formed to pass\nthrough many of the principal\nstreets en route to a railway sta\ntion.\nPolice to Assist.\nPolice promised every assistance\nand asked co-operation by the Sinn\nFein to prevent any demonstration.\nThey urged that the marchers re\nfrain from carrying flags or banners\nor concersing with spectators.\nWith three of Ireland\u2019s hunger\nstrikers now dead, it was reported\nthree more in Cork jail were near\ncollapse.\nThe news of MacSwiney\u2019s death\nwas followed quickly by that of an\nother hunger striker, Joseph\nTurn to Page Two, Column Six.\nRENEW RECRUITING FOR\nARMY OF OCCUPATION\nWASHINGTON Recruiting for\nthe Army of Occupation now on\nduty in Germany will be resumed on\nNov. 1. For the infantry 200 men\nare needed, of whom 12 must be\nclerks, but only recruits of high\ntype, who can be quickly trained,\nwill be accepted.\nTHAT\u2019S WHY LABORERS\u2019\nWIVES SHOULD VOTE\nST. PAUL\u2014One precinct, with 50\nper cent more women than men vot\ners. will be watched with interest by\npoliticians here a week from today.\nThe third precinct of the seventh\n(\u201csilk stocking\u201d) ward registered\n676 women. There are 426 men on\nthe booWs.\nFINDS STRANGE CIGARETS\nIN HOME; WINS DIVORCE\nCHICAGO \u2014Mark Flexner won a\ndivorce on the strength of a cig\narette. He found burnt cigarettes in\nhis home when he returned home\nfrom a trip. \u201cThey weren\u2019t the kind\nI smoke,\u201d he testified.\nf\nMilwaukee and vicinity: Unsettled and\ncooler tonight; possible rain. Wednesday\npartly cloudy and cooler. Moderate vari\nable winds, becoming northwest Wednes\nday.\nWisconsin: Unsettled tonight and with\npossib\u2019y rain in extreme south portion.\nCooler in northwest and southeast portions.\nWednesday partly cloudy and cooler.\nTemperatures: 1 a. m.. 53; 2, 52; 3 52;\n4. 52: 5. 52; 6, 51: 7. 52: S. 53: 9? 58; 10.\n53: 11, 55: noon. 54.\nTemperature 2 J hours to midnight: Max\nimum, 56; minirrAim. 14: mean 56; normal,\n46. Midnight to 10 a. m Minimum. 51;\nrelative humidity. 86; wind velocity at 7\na. ni\u201e 9 miles: direction of wind at 7 a. m.,\nnortheast; sunrise today, 6:19; sunset, 4:53.\nThe Milwaukee Leader\nAid. Reynolds, Socialist, to\nAsk Council Express Its\nSympathy for Widow.\n\u201cMAYOR PROVED LIBERTY\nSTILL WORTH DYING FOR\u201d\nBells Throughout State Will\nToll for Irish Martyr Next\nSunday.\nThat the common council will\nbe asked to supplement through\nadoption of a'condolence resolu\ntion, the cablegram of sympathy\nMayor Daniel W. Hoan yesterday\nsent to Mrs. Muriel MacSwiney,\nwidow of Terence MacSwiney,\nlord mayor of Cork, who died in\nBrixton prison, London, on the\n74th day of his hunger strike in\nprotest against his imprisonment\nby the English government, was\nindicated today.\nAid. Thomas Reynolds, Socialist,\nsth ward, announced that he will\nintroduce such a condolence resolu\ntion, in the council in its next meet\ning Monday.\n\u201cAttracted The World.\u201d\n\u201cI believe the council unhesitat\ningly should adopt an expression of\nsympathy for Mrs. MacSwiney,\u201d Aid.\nReynolds said. \u201cShe is the widow\nof a man who proved by giving up\nhis life that liberty still is a thing\nworth fighting and dying for. His\ndeath has attracted the attention of\nthe world to the oppression which\nhe contended is being heaped upon\nIreland by the British government.\u201d\nThere will be a special services in\nchurches throughout Wisconsin Sun\nday, out of respect to the memory\nof MacSwiney, according to word\ngiven out by the I\u2018ocal organization\nof the Friends of Irish Freedom to- 1\nday.\nTo Demand Recognition.\nAccompanying the religious serv\nices it is expected that Badger so\ncieties will draw up f ^re&;>lutions ex\npressing sympathy the relatives\nor MacSwiney and tot yig\" Irish re\npublic and demanding that the Unit\ned States government recognize the\nrepublic of Ireland. It is also ex\npected that demonstrations and pub\nlic processions will be organized.\nA flood of telegrams was received 1\nat the office of the Friehds of Irish I\nFreedom in the Pereles Bldg. today,]\nfrom all corners of the .state saying'\nthat out of reverence for the late\nLord Mayor of Cork, and at the\nsame time the deathknell of British\nautocracy, the church bells were\ntolling.\nHammond Bells Toll.\nThe following are some of the\ntelegrams received at the local office:\nHammond, Wis., Oct. 25, 1920.\nTo Joseph P. Callen.\nPereless Bldg., Milwaukee.\nBells of Hammond tolling for\nMacSwiney. Deathknell of British\nautocracy.\nFATHER CUNNINGHAM.\nMineral Point, Wis. Oct. 25, 1920.\nTo Joseph P. Callan,\nPereless Bldg., Milwaukee.\nBells tolling in all Catholic\nchurches acocunt MacSwiney death.\nREV. L. P. O\u2019REILEY.\nMarinette Observes Death.\nMarinette, Wis.. Oct. 25, 1920.\nTo Joseph P. Callan,\nPereless Bldg., Milwaukee.\nChurch bells tolling in memory of\nIreland\u2019s martyred mayor.\nJOHN MOORE.\nOschkosh, Wis., Oct. 25, 1920.\nTo Joseph P. Callan,\nPereless Bldg., Milwaukee.\nBells tolled in five churches out\nof respect MacSwiney today.\nCARL B. MACCABE..\nPlatteville, Wis. Oct. 25, 1920.\nTo Joseph P. Callan,\nPereless Bldg., Milwaukee.\nThe bells of this city tolling out of\nrespect to the memory of Mac-\nSwiney. JOSEPH DOLAN.\nAt Tomahawk. Too.\nTomahawk, Wis., Oct. 35, 1920.\nTo Joseph P. Callan,\nPereless Bldg., Milwaukee.\nBells tolled at 3 p. m. to honor\ndeath of MacSwiney.\nP. J. GAHAN.\nEau Claire, Wis., Oct. 25, 1920.\nTo Joseph P. Callan,\nPereless Bldg., Milwaukee.\nBells on St. Patricks church\ntolled on news of death of Lord\nMayor MacSwiney.\nJ. W. SINGLETON.\nWIFE TAPPED SALOON\nTILL TO BUY LIQUOR\nAT DRUG STORE, CLAIM\nHarry Chudy. a saloonkeeper, in\na divorce complaint filed Tuesday,\ncharges that his wife, Katie, made a\npractice of tapping the till in his\nsaloon and then going to a drug store\nto buy liquor. He claims she ne\nglected the children and is frequent\nly intoxicated. They were married\ninAugust, 1913, and he asks the\ncustody of their two children.\nBIG PACKERSOFFER NEW\nSCHEME TO \u201cSELL\u201d YARDS\nWASHINGTON\u2014A new plan for\ndisposal Of packer interests in stock\nyards under the recent dissolution\nagreement made _ with government\nwas submitted to the District of Co\nlumbia supreme court today. The\ndepartment of justice announced it\nis considering the plan, which pro\nvides five trustees to handle the\nstockyards for a period of 20 years,\nduring which the packers would\ngradually dispcs? of their interests\nto producers and livestock men. The\ntrustees would be appointed by the\ncourt.\n\"UNAWED BY INFLUENCE AND UNERIBED BY GAIN\"\nTUESDAY EVENING, OCTOBER 26, 1920.\nNOW DONT GET\nHF flustered old man\nBg WHY. 1 LIKE IT UP HEXE\nBl SPLEndiq VIEWANP iOS\nL TH AT W SAY'Wm\nHow LONG\nAH e You going _Eo\nto rang\nf i Hl\nliBEM\nly \u25a02^\u201c\njg /hEYH FOR THE LOVE?\nO\u2019 MINE SEND THAT y\nyr I BIWD DOWN HERE\u2019\n\u2014Hedenstein in The Minnesota Star.\nHU MOS\nMEcmmu\nmm.\nNo Improvement Seen This\nYear by Owners.\nThe general industrial depression\nwith its attendant unemployment\nand wage reductions has extended\nIts grip to the lumber and building\nindustries, according to local lum\nbermen, who stated today that .sev\neral Wisconsin mills had already\nshut down and lumber yards here\nare running on a 60 per cent basis.\n\u201cAs a result of the rapid drop in\nprices of lumber and the lack of\npurchasers, business is about 60 per\ncent of normal,\u201d an announcement\nof the Froedtert Dumber Co. .stated.\n\u201cEverybody is laying low, expecting\na further reduction and there will\nbe no improvement until next spring\nwith the resumption of building ac\ntivities. While we have not laid off\nany men in our yards as yet. build\ning labor undoubtedly will experi\nence the effects of the big slump and\nquite a number of carpenters, we\nTprn to Page Two, Column Eight.\nSpeaking About the \u201cSolemn Referendum\u201d Before Making Peace:\nWhy didn\u2019t Woodrow Wilson ask for a\n\u201csolemn referendum\u201d before he plunged\nthis country into the war?\nThe Socialist party did. The Milwaukee\nLeader did.\nBut neither Wilson, nor the Republican\nparty, dared to risk a referendum \u2014solemn\nor otherwise.\nAnd why did not Mr. Wilson ask lor a\nreferendum before he had his Republican-\nDemocratic rubber stamp Congress pass\nthe Prohibition Act?\nWhy did he not ask for a referendum be\nfore his Republican-Democratic Congress\ndecreed conscription at his behest?\n\nWhy did he not ask for a referendum be\nfore he had his Republican-Democratic rub\nber stamps approve the infamous Espionage\nLaw? It created 700,000 official spies in\nthis country. It encouraged yellow paint\nSKYLARKING!\nSEVENFIUEDFOR\nSELLING BELOW\nSTANDARD, MILK\nSeven restaurant keepers were ar\nraigned in district court this morn\ning and fined $5 and costs each on a\ncharge of selling adulterated milk.\nThe move is the first in a cam\npaign against all city restauran^,\nw*hieh are selling below standard\nmilk. Thirteen more warrants, is\nsued today, will be returned in dis\ntrict court tomorrow.\nAccoiding to R. W. Cunliffe, city\nchemist, all samples tak^n contained\nless than 3 'per cent butter fat.\nThe following were fined: Mrs.\nThomas Stokla, 810 Statje St.; W. E.\nThomas, 602 Cedar St,; Dee Thomas,\n326 4th St.; Em,il Filkovict, 391 3rd\nSt.; E. Moore, 264 4th St.; Mary\nSiefert, 312 Reed St.; and W. 13.\nKeyes, 217 Wisconsin Si\nWarrants were issued for the fol\nlowing: Frank Sax?, 134' Grand\nAve.; W. W. Desmond. 622 Grand\nAve. Joseph P. Kalt, 230 Grand\nAve.; B. Eransky, 1076 Oakland\nAve.; Tony Adams, 109 4th St.;\nGeorge Jolmovoulaf, Sycamore St.;\nAntoine Sekolonik, 200 Reed St.; E.\nKostuike, 29 0 National Ave.; Gus\nConstanlokopilas, 331 Wells St.; J.\nOrtman, 331 Fond du Dac Ave.; Mrs.\nBertha. Witt, 294 Prairie St.; Her\nman Rhmann, 782 3rd St.; B, C.\nBrown, 451 Farwell Ave.\nCounty officials declare that after\nbrigades, and terrorism, against loyal citi\nzens and innocent aliens.\n\nIn order to make peace, however\u2014peace\neven two years alter the armistice was\nsigned on the basis of his 14 lies\u2014Wilson\nwants a \u201csolemn referendum.\u201d\nI\nGive it to him on Nov. 2. And make it\nvery solemn. Solemn enough to remind\nHarding and the Republican senators and\ncongressmen that they had voted for all\ni these measures. That they helped Wilson\nto plunge us into the war. That they helped\nto create terrorism, the high cost of living,\nprofiteering and panics. That they helped\nto take away our liberty of speech, our\nfree press, and our right to free assemblage.\n\nIncidentally, Mr. and Mrs. Voter, also re\nmind your neighbor that a vote for the\nRepublican ticket is an indorsement of all\nI these things. That such a vote is an in-\nAGREEMTIN\nENGLISH MINE\nSTRIKE SEEN\nAll Executives Now in Confer\nence With Lloyd George.\nBY CHARDES M\u2019CANN.\nUnited Press Staff Correspondent.\nLONDON \u2014An agreement to end\nthe^ British coal strike appeared at\nhand today. All miners\u2019 union ex\necutives attended a conference with\nPremier Dlpyd George at 11:30 a.\nm., indicating formal negotiations\nhad replaced \u201cconversations.\u201d\nFrank Hodges, secretary of the\nminers\u2019 federation, supported t at\ninterpretation, when he said the\nconference of delegates would decide\nwhether the proposed terms should\nbe approved and submitted to a\nunion ballot\nThe terms were said unofficially\nTurn to Page Four. Column Seven.\nthe \u201ccleanlup\u201d in Milwaukee is ac\ncomplished, steps will be taken to\nprosecute dairymen who are believed\nto b; partially guilty for some of the\nviolations.\nFINANCIAL DEPRESSION\nWITH SERIOUS RESULTS\nIS FEAR OF FINANCIERS\nGreat Precautions Must Be Taken it Low Trade Barometer Is\nNot to Presage Wave of Collapses, Money\nDealers Agree.\nASSERT NATION-WIDE PANIC MAY BE AVERTED\nBusiness failures and a financial depression here that will bring\nserious consequences unless great care is exercised, were predicted\ntoday by Milwaukee bankers on the heels of reports of thousands\nof workers being laid off in industries.\nDISGUSTWILL\nGARRY BADGER\nVOTEFORG.O.P.\nVICTOR L. BERGER.\nEspionage Law Will Be Dem\nocratic Party\u2019s Knell.\nThe Republican presidential can\ndidate will carry Wisconsin in the\nNov. 2 election \u201cby disgust\u201d and\nCox will not carry a single one of\nthe state\u2019s 71 counties, according to\npredictions voiced by Victor D.\nBerger, Socialist candidate for con\ngress, sti district, last night? before\nan enthusiastic audience that filled\nMetropolitan hall, Clarke and 6th\nSts.\nThe other speakers were Leo\nKrzycki, candidate for sheriff, and\nAid. John Doerfler, 7th ward. The\nchairman was Alex Ruffing, as\nsembly candidate.\nDemocrats Will Die.\n\u201cThe Democratic party is going\nto die in the coming election, just\nas the Federalist party succumbed\nmore than 100 years asro, after\nsponsoring the alien and seditirX\nlaw, which is far less cruel tliar\nthe espionage law W'hich still is in\neffect although the armistice was\nsigned nearly two years ago,\u201d Ber\nger said.\n\"You had war, conscription ,an es\npionage act and yellow paint under\nthe Democratic administration the\nlast few years. If you vote the Re\npublican ticket in the coming elec\ntion, you indorse war. the espionage\nact and yellow paint brigades.\n\u201cThe Democrats have lost the sup\nport of the German-Americans,\nIrish-Americans and railroad men.\u201d\nArgues For Berger.\nAid. Doerfler contrasted the bar\nring of Berger from /the seat in con\ngress to which he had been twice\nelected by the sth district, with the\ncase of an Italian labor leader, who\nopposed the war, fled to Switzerland\nand returned to Italy at its close\nand was elected to parliament and\nseated.\nI \"Berger was denied the seat to\n1 which he twice was elected in a so-\nI called democratic republic,\u201d said the\naiderman. \u201cBut the Italian labor\nleader was seated in a monarchy's\nlaw-making body.\u201d\nSees More Militarism.\nAid. Doerfler expressed the onin\nion that Senator Robert M. La Fol\nlette would vote for\u00ae Berger, if he\nwere a resident of the sth district.\n'He said La Follette, in nis recent\nAuditorium meeting did not say a\nword in approval of the Republican\nnational ticket and would have in-\ndorsed Berger, but for the fact that\n;he confined himself to a manu\nscript.\n\u201cI challenge Senator La Follette\nto deny the truth of my, opinion\u201d\nsaid Aid. Doerfler.\nKrzycki predicted that other\nstates, following election, will pass\nlaws modeled on the one that re\ncently went into effect in New York\nstate, preventing boys between 16\nand 19 years of age, from going\nto school or obtaining employment,\nif they do not enroll for military\ntraining.\ndorsement of the war, of the Espionage Act\nand of the yellow paint brigade.\n\nAlso remind your neighbor that neither\nMr. Kleczka nor Mr. Stafford can possibly\nrepresent him. That Mr. Stafford has not\nbeen missed at all in the House during the\nlast two years, because Wall Street had\nplenty of other messenger boys left there.\nAnd that the voters of the Fifth District\nof Milwaukee can not permit the profiteers\nand the 323 lawyers in the House of Repre\nsentatives to dictate to them for whom they\nare to vote. If the voters would submit\u2014\nthat would be the end of representative\ngovernment.\n\nFor this reason, and for every other rea\nson, the safe thing and the only thing to do\nis to vote the Socialist ticket straight. And\nit is also the only protest vote. There is\nno other.\nMake it a \u201csolemn referendum,\u201d men and\nwomen of Milwaukee.\nHOME\nEDITION\nPRICE THREE CENTS.\nvice president,\ntlonal Bank of Commerce, asserted\nthe country is in a period of buafr\nness and financial adjustment which\nalways follows periods such as w 4\nhave just passed through.\n\u201cBusiness failures are surely com.\ning and unless great precaution is\ntaken by business concerns It will bq\nserious,\u201d he said. We expect that\nthere will be a let up in the present\nhigh cost of money after Christmai\nand with it will come an easing of\nthe present depression.\nNo Chance for Panic.\ns \"There is no chance for a finan*\ncial panic but business may suffei\nto a great extent before the adjust*\nment will be completed. No one\ncan say what time will pass before\nthe business and financial world will\nagain be stable hut we are hoping\nthat it will be within a brief peri*\nod.\u201d\nThere is no chance, for a panic to\ndevelop from the present business\ndepression according to G. L.\nWeigle, cashier, Second Ward Sav*\nings bank.\nSaid Weigle:\nThe present start in the\nway of depression may de\nvelop great momentum and cause\nmany failures in business, but the\nfederal reserve system will save\nthe banks from any financial dis\naster or panic.\nLoans Are Secured.\nThe repudiation of war debts\nby European countries which\nhave borrowed money will not\nhave any effect, on a financial\ncrisis as the loans have all been\nmade through the government.\nThe securities which the banks\nho\u2019d, .^oh as Liberty bonds, will\n,be goo'S as long as the govern\n;ment good. When the time\ncomis that government securities\nare no good, then no banks will\nbe able to keep up.\nThe only private loans which\nhave been made to European\ncountries were carried on by The\nNational City bank and J. P. Mor\ngan Co. These loans, however,\nare for the running of private\nbusiness so the repudiation or the\nloss of these would not affect the\nbanking systems of the country\nto any great extent.\nFears Financial Crash.\nAll of the indications of a great\nbusiness depression are on us now,\nand if these keep Increasing in vol*\nume, added to by war debt repudia*\ntion, there is a great probability of a\nfinancial crash in the future, de*\ndared Thomas Duncan, private sec^\nretary to Mayor D. W. Hoan, for*\nmerly connected with the Wisconsin\nTrust Co's, department.\nDuncan said:\nThe great steel industry is the\nbarometer by which business de\npression may be estimated. In the\npast two monthly reports of this\nindustry it is stated that orders\nhave been received for about 10,-\n000,0Q0 tons of steel, a consider\nable decrease from that of previ\nous months. If these orders should\nfall as low as 4,000,000 tons per\nmonth we would have a period of\nserious business depression.\nAdd to Unemployment.\nThis curtailment of orders\nwould cause at least 250,000\nmen to be laid off. When these\nworkers are not allowed to earn,\ntheir buying power is immediately\nended. In this way sales which\nhad been made to them before\nwould stop, and industries, such as\nthe textile, would have to slow\ndown and finally stop, placing\nmore persons out of work with\nfurther curtailment of sales. When\nonce this wave is started it will\nspread to most ail of the industries\nand cause the industrial world to\nstop functioning.\nIf, on top of this big business\ndepression, comes the repudiation\nof war loans to Italy, France and\nEngland, there is great possibility\nof a financial crash.\nThe business depression is sure\nly coming on us. The possibility\nof war debt repudiation is not\nslight and with the combination\nof the two a financial disaster\nw\u2019ould be hArd to stop.\nLIBERTY BONDS. AT LEAST,\nARE LOWER, WOMAN SAYS\nNEW YORK\u2014It was at a meet\nj ing of the Harding Democratic\nI league at Yorkville Lyceum last\nnight. Henry Fairless of Virginia\nspoke.\n\u201cCan anybody name one article\nthat has decreased in price in the\nlast seven and a half years?\u201d he\nsaid.\nA woman in the rear of the audi\nence answered:\n\u201cYes; Liberty bonds!\u201d\nMAN ANdTbOYSDIE\nIN MINNEAPOLIS CAVEINS\nMINNEAPOLIS\u2014-One man and\ni three boys wore killed in two sand\nI caveins late yesterday at almost the\ni same time. Five boys, digging sand\ni caves, were caught in an avalanche\nof sand and three smothered to\ndeath. The other two will recover.\nJohn Bram-id, aged 35. was buried\neight feet deep in a sewer Utah\nabout the same time,","height":"28101","width":"22161"}}
